Verifying Recurrence Relation of Bessel's Function :¶

xJ_n'(x)+nJ_n(x)=xJ_(v-1)(x)

In [5]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.special import jv,jvp

v=eval(input("Enter the order of Bessel's Function : "))			       #can be non-integer value
a=eval(input('Enter lower limit of z value : '))
b=eval(input('Enter upper limit of z value : '))
n=int(input('Enter the no. of subintervals : '))

zval=np.linspace(a,b,n)
L=zval*jvp(v,zval)+v*jv(v,zval)
R=zval*jv(v-1,zval)

tolerance=eval(input('Enter Tolerance : '))
for i in range(n):
	if abs(L[i]-R[i])<tolerance:
		flag=True
	else:
		flag=False

if flag==True:
	print('Recurrence Relation is verified')
else:
	print('Recurrence relation is not satisfied')

plt.title('Graph for recurrence formula of Bessels Function')
plt.xlabel('Z')
plt.ylabel('Solution')
plt.plot(zval,L,'r--',label='L.H.S')
plt.plot(zval[::4],R[::4],'bo',ms='5',label='R.H.S')
plt.axhline(color="gray")
plt.axvline(color="gray")
plt.legend()
plt.grid()
plt.show()

Recurrence Relation is verified

Verifying Recurrence Relation of Bessel's Function :¶

J_n'(x)=0.5[J_(n-1)(x)-J_(n+1)(x)]

Verifying orthogonal property of Bessel's Function¶

In [19]:
import numpy as np
from scipy.special import jv,jn_zeros
from scipy.integrate import simpson

v=int(input('Enter the order : '))		#Must be integer for this property and jv_zeros takes integer v as argument
u=int(input('Enter the number of roots to generate : '))
p=int(input('Enter the order of 1st root : '))
q=int(input('Enter the order of 2nd root : '))

if (p+1)<=u and (q+1)<=u:
    n=int(input('Enter the no. of subintervals : '))
    zval=np.linspace(0,1,n)
	
    def ortho(zval,v,alpha,beta):		#alpha, beta are the roots of the polynomial and not random numbers
        I0=zval*jv(v,alpha*zval)*jv(v,beta*zval)
        return I0

    r=jn_zeros(v,u)			#Generates roots of the polynomial. u indicates u roots in increasing order in an array 
    I1=simpson(ortho(zval,v,r[p],r[q]),zval)
    I2=simpson(ortho(zval,v,r[p],r[p]),zval)
    R2=0.5*(jv(v+1,r[p]))**2
    I3=simpson(ortho(zval,v,r[q],r[q]),zval)
    R3=0.5*(jv(v+1,r[q]))**2
	
    err=0.001
    if I1<err:
        print('Bessels Orthogonality is verified when roots are not equal i.e taking roots', r[p],'and',r[q],'and the value of the integral is :',I1)

    else:
        print('Bessels Orthogonality is not verified when roots are not equal i.e taking roots',r[p],'and',r[q])
 
   
    if abs(I2-R2)<err:
        print('Bessels Orthogonality is verified when roots are equal i.e taking roots',r[p],'and',r[p],' and the value of the integral is :',I2)
    else:
        print('Bessels Orthogonality is not verified when roots are equal i.e taking roots',r[p],'and',r[p])
	
	
    if abs(I3-R3)<err:
        print('Bessels Orthogonality is verified when roots are equal i.e taking roots',r[q],'and',r[q],' and the value of the integral is :',I3)
    else:
        print('Bessels Orthogonality is not verified when roots are equal i.e taking roots',r[q],'and',r[q])
		
else:
    print('Order of root cannot be more than number of roots generated')

Bessels Orthogonality is verified when roots are not equal i.e taking roots 13.589290170541217 and 90.12238682807623 and the value of the integral is : 2.4452049389469445e-06
Bessels Orthogonality is verified when roots are equal i.e taking roots 13.589290170541217 and 13.589290170541217  and the value of the integral is : 0.02106327831439192
Bessels Orthogonality is verified when roots are equal i.e taking roots 90.12238682807623 and 90.12238682807623  and the value of the integral is : 0.0035334054171536847

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.special import jv,jvp

t=int(input('Enter for the positive order : '))
u=int(input('Enter for the negative order : '))
v=float(input('Enter for the positive fractional order : ')) 
w=float(input('Enter for the negative fractional order : '))             
a=eval(input('Enter lower limit of z value : '))
b=eval(input('Enter upper limit of z value : '))
n=int(input('Enter the no. of subintervals : '))

zval=np.linspace(a,b,n)
I1=jv(abs(t),zval)
I2=jv(-abs(u),zval)
I3=jv(abs(v),zval)
I4=jv(-abs(w),zval)


plt.suptitle('Graph for solution of Bessels Function for types of order')


plt.subplot(2,2,1)
plt.plot(zval,I1,'r-',label='positive order')
plt.xlabel('Z')
plt.ylabel('Solution')
plt.axhline(color="black",lw=0.5)
plt.axvline(color="black",lw=0.5)
plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.grid()

plt.subplot(2,2,2)
plt.plot(zval,I2,'g-',label='negative order')
plt.xlabel('Z')
plt.ylabel('Solution')
plt.axhline(color="black",lw=0.5)
plt.axvline(color="black",lw=0.5)
plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.grid()

plt.subplot(2,2,3)
plt.plot(zval,I3,'b-',label='positive fractional order')
plt.xlabel('Z')
plt.ylabel('Solution')
plt.axhline(color="black",lw=0.5)
plt.axvline(color="black",lw=0.5)
plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.grid()

plt.subplot(2,2,4)
plt.plot(zval,I4,'y-',label='negative fractional order')
plt.xlabel('Z')
plt.ylabel('Solution')
plt.axhline(color="black",lw=0.5)
plt.axvline(color="black",lw=0.5)
plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.grid()

plt.show()

Verifying Recurrrence relation of Legendre Polynomial :¶

(1-x^2)P_n'(x)=(n+1)xP_n(x)-(n+1)P_(n+1)(x)

In [37]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.special import legendre as P

m=int(input('Enter no. of subintervals : '))
a,b=eval(input('Enter lower and upper limits of interval : '))
n=int(input('Enter the order of polynomial : '))       #must be positive integer

x=np.linspace(a,b,m)
dPn=np.polyder(P(n))
L=np.poly1d([-1,0,1])*dPn                #The polynomial can't be just written (as, 1-x**2) as the operand with P will not support it
R=(n+1)*np.poly1d([1,0])*P(n)-(n+1)*P(n+1)

err=0.0001
for i in range(m):
    if abs(L[i]-R[i])<err:
        flag=True
    else:
        flag=False
        break
    
if flag==True:
    print('Recurrence Relation is satisfied')
else:
    print('Recurrence Relation is not satisfied')
    
plt.title('Graph for Recurrence formula of Legendre Function')
plt.xlabel('X')
plt.ylabel('Solution')
plt.plot(x,L(x),'r--',label='L.H.S')
plt.plot(x[::4],R(x)[::4],'bo',ms='5',label='R.H.S')
plt.axhline(color="gray")
plt.axvline(color="gray")
plt.legend()
plt.grid()

Recurrence Relation is satisfied

# Verifying Recurrrence relation of Legendre Polynomial : 
(n+1)P_(n+1)(x)=(2n+1)xP_n(x)-nP_(n-1)(x)

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.special import legendre as P

m=int(input('Enter no. of subintervals : '))
a,b=eval(input('Enter lower and upper limits of interval : '))
n=int(input('Enter the order of polynomial : '))       #must be positive integer

x=np.linspace(a,b,m)
L=(n+1)*P(n+1)
R=(2*n+1)*np.poly1d([1,0])*P(n)-n*P(n-1)

err=0.0001
for i in range(m):
    if abs(L[i]-R[i])<err:
        flag=True
    else:
        flag=False
        break
    
if flag==True:
    print('Recurrence Relation is satisfied')
else:
    print('Recurrence Relation is not satisfied')

plt.axvline(color="gray")
plt.legend()
plt.grid()

Verifying Orthogonal relation of Legendre Polynomial¶

In [49]:
import numpy as np
from scipy.integrate import simpson
from scipy.special import legendre as P

n=int(input('Enter the order of polynomial : '))
m=n+1
fun1=P(n)*P(m)
N=int(input('Enter the no. of subintervals : '))

x=np.linspace(-1,1,N)
I1=simpson(fun1(x),x)

err=0.0001
if I1<err:
    print('Orthogonality checked for unequal order', n,m)
else:
    print('Orthogonality is not satisfied for unequal order', n,m)    
    
fun2=P(n)*P(n)
I2=simpson(fun2(x),x)  
if abs(I2-2/(2*n+1))<err:
     print('Orthogonality checked for equal order', n,n)
else:
    print('Orthogonality is not satisfied for equal', n,n) 

Orthogonality checked for unequal order 3 4
Orthogonality checked for equal order 3 3

import numpy as np
from scipy.integrate import simpson
from scipy.special import legendre as P

n=int(input('Enter the order of polynomial : '))
N=int(input('Enter the no. of subintervals : '))
x=np.linspace(-1,1,N)

err=0.001

print('n\tm\tDelta\t\tResult')
print('---------------------------------------------------')

def Int(n,m):
    fun=P(n)*P(m)
    I=(2*n+1)/2*simpson(fun(x),x)
    return I
    
for m in range (0,n+2):
    I=Int(n,n)
    if I<err or I-1<err:    	
    	print('%d\t%d\t%0.2f'%(n,m,Int(n,m)),'  Orthogonality  is satisfied')
    else:
    	print('%d\t%d\t%0.2f'%(n,m,Int(n,m)),'  Orthogonality  is not satisfied')  

n	m	Delta		Result
---------------------------------------------------
3	0	0.00   Orthogonality  is satisfied
3	1	0.00   Orthogonality  is satisfied
3	2	0.00   Orthogonality  is satisfied
3	3	1.00   Orthogonality  is satisfied
3	4	0.00   Orthogonality  is satisfied

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.special import legendre as P

t=int(input('Enter for the order of Legendre polynomial : '))
u=int(input('Enter for the order of derivative of Legendre polynomial : '))            
a=eval(input('Enter lower limit of z value : '))
b=eval(input('Enter upper limit of z value : '))
n=int(input('Enter the no. of subintervals : '))

zval=np.linspace(a,b,n)
I1=P(t)
I2=np.polyder(P(u))

plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
plt.suptitle('Graph for solution of Legendre polynomial and its derivative')

plt.subplot(1,2,1)
plt.plot(zval,I1(zval),'r-',label='Legendre polynomial')
plt.xlabel('Z')
plt.ylabel('Solution')
plt.axhline(color="black",lw=0.5)
plt.axvline(color="black",lw=0.5)
plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.grid()

plt.subplot(1,2,2)
plt.plot(zval,I2(zval),'g-',label='Derivative of Legendre polynomial')
plt.xlabel('Z')
plt.ylabel('Solution')
plt.axhline(color="black",lw=0.5)
plt.axvline(color="black",lw=0.5)
plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.grid()

plt.show()
